The children received gifts that included clothing, toys and hygiene products, while food hampers were handed to their parents.
Those children who were not able to leave their hospital beds for the party were also given party packs and lunch.
Ryan said the foundation aimed to educate and empower the parents of children with special needs.

She said the parents should not lose hope.
“Your children are special to you. God has given them to you for a reason, so pay attention to them. Take extra care and they will thrive and do better,” she said.
King Edward VIII Hospital chief executive Dr Mandla Mazizi said a child was a child, irrespective of his or her physical or mental disposition.

“Especially at this time of the year, it gives us a lot of pleasure to be able to do something for children, as we are also about to celebrate Christmas,” he said.
The Mercury